1. What are logical operators in Java?
-->Logical operators are used to combine or manipulate boolean values (true / false).
    Main logical operators:
    && → Logical AND
    || → Logical OR
    ! → Logical NOT
    📌 Example:
    boolean a = true;
    boolean b = false;
    System.out.println(a && b); // false
    System.out.println(a || b); // true
    System.out.println(!a);     // false


2. What is short-circuit evaluation?
-->Short-circuit evaluation in Java is a mechanism where logical operators (&& and ||) stop evaluating subsequent conditions in a boolean expression if 
    the final result is already determined by the first operand. It improves performance and prevents errors (like NullPointerException) by skipping 
    unnecessary checks if the outcome is guaranteed.

    Short-circuit evaluation means:
      👉 Java stops evaluating the expression as soon as the result is known. 
      In && → if first condition is false, second is NOT checked
      In || → if first condition is true, second is NOT checked
      📌 Example:
      int a = 10;
      if (a > 5 || ++a > 10) {
          System.out.println(a); // 10 (second condition not executed)
      }


3. What is the difference between & and &&?
-->
| Feature    | `&`                                | `&&`                      |
| ---------- | ---------------------------------- | ------------------------- |
| Type       | Bitwise / Logical                  | Logical                   |
| Evaluation | Evaluates **both sides always**    | Uses **short-circuit**    |
| Use case   | Bit operations / sometimes boolean | Mostly used in conditions |

    
    int a = 5;
    
    if (false & (++a > 0)) {
        // a will still increment
    }
    
    if (false && (++a > 0)) {
        // a will NOT increment
    }



4. What is the result of combining true/false values using logical operators?
-->
| Expression       | Result |        |       |
| ---------------- | ------ | ------ | ----- |
| `true && true`   | true   |        |       |
| `true && false`  | false  |        |       |
| `false && true`  | false  |        |       |
| `false && false` | false  |        |       |
| `true            |        | false` | true  |
| `false           |        | false` | false |
| `!true`          | false  |        |       |
| `!false`         | true   |        |       |



5. Can logical operators be applied to non-boolean operands?
-->No, logical operators in Java cannot be applied to non-boolean operands. 
    Unlike languages such as JavaScript or C++, Java strictly requires operands of logical operators to be of the boolean type or expressions that 
    resolve to a boolean.
    boolean a = true;
    boolean b = false;
    
    System.out.println(a && b); // false
    System.out.println(a || b); // true
    System.out.println(!a);     // false
